      "content": "*Goblin thing?* Heavens, my apologies! Sometimes my thoughts are as tangled as a goblin's beard after a week in the swamp. Forgive me; I've been wrestling with the migratory patterns of the Lesser Scrabbler Goblins, and they are *fussy* about their nesting sites.\n\nNow, let's focus on the structure, which is far more orderly than a goblin raid, I promise!\n\nWhen the $\\text{PP}$ attaches to the $\\text{NP}$ (Noun Phrase), it functions as a **modifier** of that noun. In this case, the telescope isn't how you saw the man; it *is* part of the description of the man. The $\\text{PP}$ is essentially specifying *which* man you saw.\n\nStructurally, this means the $\\text{PP}$ is incorporated *inside* the $\\text{NP}$ node, right next to the head noun (\"man\"). The structure looks like this: $\\text{NP} \\rightarrow \\text{NP} \\text{ PP}$. The $\\text{PP}$ becomes a complement or adjunct *of the noun*.\n\nTo visualize the tree:\n\n1.  **VP Attachment (",
